Event listeners that don't call preventDefault can be [marked as passive to improve performance](https://github.com/WICG/EventListenerOptions/blob/gh-pages/explainer.md).
So, unless there is a good reason to call `event.preventDefault`, event listeners should be marked passive, particularly in performance critical sections of the code, such as scrolling.

**Steps which explain the enhancement**

1. Current calls to `event.preventDefault` in performance critical code should be evaluated to see if they are necessary
2. If they are not necessary, they should be removed
3. the event listener should be marked as passive by passing an object with a property of passive set to true, i.e. `{passive: true}`, as the third parameter to `addEventListener`

**Current and suggested behavior**

Currently [searching for "passive" in the atom repo](https://github.com/atom/atom/search?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=passive) doesn't show any event listeners marked as passive, and [searching issues for passive](https://github.com/atom/atom/issues?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=passive) doesn't show this being suggested before.

I've been using this code in my init.js file for a little while with no obvious ill effects.

```js
(function () {
    //remove event.preventDefault() calls in TextEditorConponent's onMouseWheel listener
    atom.workspace.observeTextEditors(function (editor) {
        var component = editor.editorElement.component

        component.domNode.removeEventListener('mousewheel', component.onMouseWheel)
        
        component.domNode.addEventListener('mousewheel', (function(_this) {
            return function(event) {
                var previousScrollLeft, previousScrollTop, updatedScrollLeft, updatedScrollTop, wheelDeltaX, wheelDeltaY;
                wheelDeltaX = event.wheelDeltaX, wheelDeltaY = event.wheelDeltaY;
                if (Math.abs(wheelDeltaX) > Math.abs(wheelDeltaY)) {
                    previousScrollLeft = _this.presenter.getScrollLeft();
                    updatedScrollLeft = previousScrollLeft - Math.round(wheelDeltaX * _this.editor.getScrollSensitivity() / 100);

                    return _this.presenter.setScrollLeft(updatedScrollLeft);
                } else {
                    _this.presenter.setMouseWheelScreenRow(_this.screenRowForNode(event.target));
                    previousScrollTop = _this.presenter.getScrollTop();
                    updatedScrollTop = previousScrollTop - Math.round(wheelDeltaY * _this.editor.getScrollSensitivity() / 100);

                    return _this.presenter.setScrollTop(updatedScrollTop);
                }
            };
        })(component), {passive: true})
    })

}).call(this); 
```

It removes the `mousewheel` listener from the `TextEditorComponent` and adds another version which is almost the same except the conditional calls to `event.preventDefault` have been taken out, (and it has been converted from coffeescript to javascript), and marks it as passive. Since the calls to `event.preventDefault` don't seem to be doing anything important (at least on my system?) I think they should be removed and the event listener should be marked as passive.

**Why would the enhancement be useful to most users**

Giving the runtime more information with which to optimize could have performance improvements in many areas of the codebase. Focusing on scrolling performance alone, here are some previously opened issues related to scrolling: #10188 #10987 #13407

It's also easy to find people complaining about atom's scrolling speed elsewhere.

**Screenshots and GIFs**

One day scrolling in Atom lagged for a moment. So I opened up dev tools to see if I could collect enough info for a bug report, and the following errors were in the console. 

![passivelisteners](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2133026/21173771/b15e948e-c196-11e6-86f9-ccdbdabce596.png)


The top two are familiar, and appear to be being worked on. The third one is what prompted me to research passive event listeners and to break on `mousewheel` listeners and investigate what happens when scrolling in the text editor component enough to write the code above. Also note you can make the third type of error message happen by setting a breakpoint an a non-passive `mousewheel` listener and trying to scroll the editor and then resuming execution.

